:QUOTE
The SCOBY is not an ingredient. It is a living culture that teaches you fermentation every time you feed it.

:INFO
What a SCOBY Actually Is
SCOBY stands for Symbiotic Culture of Bacteria and Yeast. It is a rubbery disc \
of cellulose produced by acetic acid bacteria as a byproduct of fermentation. \
The bacteria and yeast live throughout the culture and in the liquid, not only \
in the disc itself. Your SCOBY grows a new layer on the surface of each batch. \
These layers can be separated, refrigerated, and shared.

:COUNTER.half
1 Cup White Sugar
Per gallon of sweet tea
|
:COUNTER.half
7 to 14 Days
First fermentation at 70 to 78 F
|
:IMAGE
scoby-health.jpg

:PATH
Brew the Sweet Tea Base
Bring 1 gallon of filtered water to a boil. Steep 4 to 6 black tea bags for \
10 minutes. Remove bags without squeezing. Add 1 cup of plain white sugar and \
stir until fully dissolved. Cool the tea completely to room temperature before \
adding the SCOBY. Heat above 90°F kills the culture. Speed up cooling by \
brewing with half the water and adding cold filtered water to fill the volume.

:PATH
Add SCOBY and Starter Liquid
Pour cooled sweet tea into a clean 1-gallon glass jar. Add the SCOBY and at \
least 1 to 2 cups of starter liquid from a previous batch or from a store-bought \
raw kombucha. Starter liquid acidifies the new batch immediately, protecting it \
from unwanted bacteria during the early days before lactic acid builds. Without \
adequate starter liquid the batch is vulnerable during the first 48 hours.

:PATH
Cover and Ferment
Cover the jar opening with a tightly woven cloth, coffee filter, or paper towel \
secured with a rubber band. Do not use a tight lid. Kombucha needs oxygen during \
first fermentation. Place in a location between 70 and 78 degrees F away from \
direct sunlight. Taste starting at day 7 by inserting a clean straw, covering \
your thumb over the end, and drawing a small sample to taste.

:INFO
What the Ferment Looks Like
Brown yeast strands will hang from the SCOBY and float through the liquid. This \
is normal. A new SCOBY layer will begin forming on the surface within 3 to 7 \
days. The liquid gradually transforms from sweet tea into a tart, lightly \
effervescent drink. Fuzzy green, black, or pink mold on the surface is not \
normal. Discard everything and start fresh if you see it.

:COUNTER.half
2.5 to 3.5 pH
Target when first fermentation is done
|
:COUNTER.half
10 to 20 Percent
Starter liquid reserved for next batch

:CHECKLIST
Before First Fermentation
[ ] Glass jar cleaned with hot water only — zero soap residue
[ ] Sweet tea confirmed at room temperature before adding SCOBY
[ ] SCOBY and at least 1 cup starter liquid added
[ ] Breathable cover secured (not a tight lid)
[ ] Location confirmed: 70 to 78 degrees F, no direct sunlight

:NOTE
Temperature Changes Everything
Below 65°F kombucha ferments very slowly and yeast can dominate, creating an \
overly alcoholic or vinegary batch. Above 80°F fermentation accelerates and can \
overshoot tartness in just a few days. If your home runs warm, taste daily from \
day 4. If it runs cool in winter, expect 14 days or longer. A seedling heat mat \
set under the jar stabilizes temperature in cooler spaces.

:QUOTE
Every batch is a calibration. Temperature, tea strength, and sugar ratio all shift the timeline. Your palate is the only instrument that counts.

